---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import SiteHeader from '../components/SiteHeader.astro';
import SiteFooter from '../components/SiteFooter.astro';
import DocsHandoff from '../components/DocsHandoff.astro';
import HarnessDiagram from '../components/HarnessDiagram.astro';

const pageTitle = 'A harness for AI in public services | Registry Stack';
const pageDescription =
  'AI agents and automation connect public systems faster than they can be governed. Registry Stack gives every asker, human or AI, a signed, minimized answer instead of the record.';

// The review questions from the docs "safer registry surfaces" page, kept as
// the practical shift in what interoperability has to answer.
const reviewQuestions = [
  'Which entity or evidence response is being requested?',
  'Which purpose, policy, and scope apply?',
  'Which fields or claims can leave the source boundary?',
  'Which semantic definition is being used?',
  'Which audit event records the access or evidence decision?',
];
---

<Base title={pageTitle} description={pageDescription}>
  <SiteHeader current="ai" />

  <main>
    <section class="hero" aria-labelledby="ai-hero-title">
      <div class="hero-inner">
        <div class="hero-copy">
          <p class="eyebrow">AI in public services</p>
          <h1 id="ai-hero-title">No AI agent is safer than the access it is given.</h1>
          <p class="hero-lead">
            Better models and better prompts reduce how often AI errs, not what a mistake can
            reach when one lands. Public services need a harness: infrastructure that decides
            what any asker can discover, may ask, gets back, and leaves behind. Registry Stack
            is that harness for registry data.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section" aria-labelledby="harness-title">
      <div class="section-inner">
        <div class="section-heading">
          <p class="eyebrow">The harness</p>
          <h2 id="harness-title">Built into the infrastructure once, inherited by every integration.</h2>
          <p>
            A harness governs every model, every vendor, and every well-meaning builder,
            including the ones who arrive after the safety review. Each request passes one
            answering point that checks authority, meaning, and criteria, then answers narrowly
            instead of exposing everything the registry holds.
          </p>
        </div>
        <HarnessDiagram variant="ai" />
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section section-muted" aria-labelledby="example-title">
      <div class="section-inner">
        <div class="section-heading">
          <p class="eyebrow">A worked example</p>
          <h2 id="example-title">Two ways to build the same integration.</h2>
          <p>
            A housing-benefit program needs to know whether applicants fall under an income
            threshold. Automation makes both versions of this integration cheap to build. Only
            one of them is safe to run.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="problem-grid">
          <article class="quiet-card">
            <h3>Copy the records</h3>
            <p>
              The obvious integration asks the income registry for the household&rsquo;s records, and
              gets them: income history, employer, every family member, copied into a second
              system. The copy goes stale the day it lands, nobody checked that the
              registry&rsquo;s gross monthly income means the rule&rsquo;s net annual, and when a
              family is wrongly refused, the denial traces back to a join no one can explain.
            </p>
          </article>
          <article class="quiet-card">
            <h3>Ask the question</h3>
            <p>
              The program asks what it actually needs to know: does this household sit below
              the threshold for this scheme? Authority is checked before any data is read, the
              fields are validated against a shared vocabulary, the criteria are evaluated
              where the data lives, and what returns is a signed yes-or-no with a validity
              window. The family can see the exchange in the audit trail and challenge it.
            </p>
          </article>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section" aria-labelledby="question-title">
      <div class="section-inner split">
        <div class="section-heading compact">
          <p class="eyebrow">The question shifts</p>
          <h2 id="question-title">From "can these systems connect?" to "is this request legitimate?"</h2>
          <p>
            AI-assisted integration lets teams build connections faster than they can understand
            the data, the authority for access, or the meaning of each field. "Can two systems
            connect?" is too weak a question for that world. A registry surface should be able
            to answer practical review questions, for every caller, human or automated.
          </p>
        </div>
        <ul class="check-list">
          {reviewQuestions.map((question) => (
            <li>{question}</li>
          ))}
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section section-muted" aria-labelledby="not-ai-title">
      <div class="section-inner">
        <div class="section-heading compact">
          <p class="eyebrow">To be clear</p>
          <h2 id="not-ai-title">Registry Stack is not an AI product.</h2>
          <p>
            AI is the context that makes safer surfaces urgent, not the promise. Registry Stack
            does not make AI eligibility decisions, automate governance, or replace semantic
            review, authorization policy, human accountability, appeal, or recourse. It gives
            every caller, human or automated, a controlled answer instead of a raw record.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>

  <DocsHandoff
    eyebrow="Read the docs"
    heading="See how policy becomes a runtime check."
    primaryLabel="Read the docs"
  />
  <SiteFooter />
</Base>
